narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: It was nice to have a class solely dedicated to problems that can arise in research. Usually, these concepts are dealt with when they come up instead of formally preparing for them before.
How to conduct an research in a right way
I learned a lot about ethics in regards to research. I also learned a lot about the hardships females and minorities face especially in the STEM field.
I gained an understanding of the ethical considerations that may arise during my research experience and career
How to advocate for myself in conversations and decisions with my PI

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: Evan is certainly the best part of this course. I wish this course was for a full semester because 6 sessions aren't enough to touch upon anything in depth.
The professor is very enthusiastic. The material is applicable. The workload is low. However, I did not like the class time.
I thought the topics covered were examined well - there were definitely things we could have had more discussion about though
Liked how we went over scenarios that we might come across in our graduate studies.

A pre-determined syllabus that was distributed to the class prior to any sessions. Also, asking for input as to what should be included (aka areas where we felt less clear/capable) prior to creating this list. The later sessions were much better with being hands on; I wish more discussion had occurred.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes, you have to take this course as a graduate student
It is required, but Evan does make it very entertaining.
Yes it was a good crash course for the topic
